rter was born February 1, 1790, less than a year after his parents Zachariah Perrin and Mary Talcott Perrin migrated by ox-sled from Hebron, Connecticut, to settle the eastern frontier of Berlin. He married Lucy Kinney of Plainfield in November 1815, lived his entire life in Berlin, and died there in May 1871 at age eighty-one."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Distributed his fortune to charity and his children","body":"Porter accumulated more property in farming than any other man before him in Berlin, according to the 1881 Vermont Historical Gazetteer. He gave a large share to charitable and religious purposes during his lifetime, distributed much of the rest among his many children, and left enough for his widow's support to her death."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 1395"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"porter-perrin-1790"},"X02394":{"id":"X02394","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"first_name":"Lucy","last_name":"Perrin","maiden_name":"Kinney","married_names":["Perrin"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Lucy Kinney Perrin"},"birth":{"year":1796,"month":10,"day":7,"city":"Plainfield","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{},"residence":{"city":"Plainfield","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"Reverend Jonathan Kinney","father_research_notes":"Rev. Jonathan Kinney of Plainfield VT. Not built — does not auto-qualify under Jalapeño Rule (no national notability). Berlin VT history (Child 1888) names him as Lucy's father."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"T01395","date_year":1815,"date_month":11,"date_day":2,"location_city":"Plainfield","location_county":"Washington","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["TD0200","TD0208","TD0209","TD0184","TD0210"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 1395 (named as wife)"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"lucy-kinney-1796"},"X01832":{"id":"X01832","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true},"tags":["revolutionary_war","vermont_migration","town_founder"],"sources":[{"label":"WikiTree — Zachariah Perrin Esq.","url":"https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Perrin-2144"},{"label":"Vermont Genealogy — Biography of Rev. James Hobart","url":"https://vermontgenealogy.com/washington/biography-of-rev-james-hobart.htm"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"T01387","date_year":1779,"location_city":"Hebron","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1828,"children_ids":["T01391","TD0120","T01393","T01394","T01395","T01396","TD0170","TD0138","T01399"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1748,"month":3,"day":18,"city":"Hebron","county":"Tolland","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1838,"month":5,"day":25,"city":"Berlin Corners","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Zachariah Perrin Esq.","first_name":"Zachariah","last_name":"Perrin","married_names":[],"suffix":"Esq.","gender":"male"},"residence":{"city":"Berlin Corners","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States","note":"Settled May 1789 from Hebron CT; farmed 1300 acres at Scott Hill/East Road intersection in East Road School District."},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM066","landmark_blurb":"Established the 1300-acre East Road farmstead and built permanent buildings here after settling Berlin VT in 1789."}],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","unit":"8th Company, 12th Regiment Connecticut Militia","notes":"Documented Revolutionary War service."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM176","plot_notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners VT."},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Settled Berlin Vermont with collapsed-roof cabin","body":"Zachariah served in the Revolutionary War with the 8th company of the 12th Connecticut militia, then in February-March 1789 led his family from Hebron Connecticut to Berlin Vermont — up the Connecticut River with two teams of oxen, switching from wheels to runners in Brookfield. They found the log cabin he had built the previous summer crushed under three or four feet of snow."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Founded a 1300-acre farm still in family","body":"Zachariah's 1300 acres in the East Road School District of Berlin VT — at what became the southeast corner of East Road and Scott Hill Road — passed down through generations of Perrins. His son Porter, the first boy born in Berlin, built the house at Scott Hill and Airport Road in 1815 (still standing). A descendant Henry Perrin still lived in 'Perrin territory' along Scott Hill Road into the modern era."}],"slug":"zachariah-perrin-1748"},"T01387":{"id":"T01387","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1758,"month":6,"day":17,"city":"Glastonbury","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1828,"month":9,"day":11,"city":"Berlin Corners","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont"},"parents":{"father_id":"T01001","mother_id":"U00042"},"marriages":[{"children_ids":["T01391","TD0120","T01393","T01394","T01395","T01396","TD0170","TD0138","T01399"],"spouse_id":"X01832","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1779,"location_city":"Hebron","location_county":"Tolland","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1828}],"sources":[{"label":"WikiTree — Mary (Talcott) Perrin","url":"https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Talcott-49"},{"label":"Clark Univ — Mary Talcott rr23/rr23_395","url":"http://aleph0.clarku.edu/~djoyce/gen/report/rr23/rr23_395.html"}],"gender":"female","tags":["vermont_migration"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_migration","related_id":"HD0233","display_label":"Settled Vermont 1789 after cousin David Newton's 1777 migration","link_text":"David Newton"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Talcott Perrin","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Perrin","maiden_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Perrin"],"gender":"female"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM066","landmark_blurb":"Lived on the Perrin family farmstead from her arrival in Berlin in 1789 until her death in 1828."}],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM176","plot_notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners VT — alongside Zachariah."},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Walked to Vermont with two oxen teams","body":"In February or March 1789 Mary and Zachariah moved their family from Hebron Connecticut to Berlin Vermont — traveling up the Connecticut River with two teams of oxen, then up the White River, switching from wheels to runners at Brookfield, then over a blazed trail. They arrived to find their log cabin's roof had collapsed under three to four feet of snow."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lost firstborn daughter Mary in 1798","body":"Mary's eldest child — also named Mary, born in Hebron — died in 1798. Four months later another daughter was born and named Mary in her sister's memory. The second Mary later married Julius Yemans Dewey and was the mother of Admiral George Dewey, hero of Manila Bay 1898."}],"slug":"mary-perrin-1758"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM176","name":"Berlin Corner Cemetery","city":"Berlin Corners","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/641556/berlin-corner-cemetery","hooker_connections":["T01387","TD0120","TD0124","TD0129","TD0158","TD0159","TD0160","TD0161","TD0162","TD0163","TD0164","TD0200","X01832","X02368","X02370","X02383","X02384","X02409"],"notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners Vermont. Burial site of the Perrin-Hobart founding family of Berlin VT — Zachariah Perrin Esq. (X01832, Berlin VT 1789 founder, Rev War vet, d.1838 age 90), his wife Mary Talcott Perrin (T01387, d.1828), their daughter Betsey Perrin Hobart (TD0120, d.1876), her husband Rev. James Hobart (X02368, Berlin VT first settled minister, d.1862 age 95), their son David Hobart (TD0129, d.1901), and his wife Caroline Reed Hobart (X02370, d.1898). Three Perrin-Hobart generations. [pilot100] Backfilled with Evans/Yale Berlin VT generation: Dr. Ira Evans Sr. (X02383) and Emeline Hobart Evans (TD0124, daughter of Rev. James + Betsey Hobart); their seven children including 4 died young/childhood/infancy (Mary E., Ira Jr., J. Annette, William Dwight) and 3 adult-lifespan (Mary Emeline Evans Yale + her Civil War vet husband Capt. Thomas Blossom Yale 108th NY Inf, Edward P. Evans 10th VT Inf wounded Cold Harbor, and Civil War Medal of Honor recipient Ira Hobart Evans TD0163 who died San Diego CA 1922 and was returned to Berlin Corner per his wishes). Cemetery now spans four generations of Hobart-Evans-Yale family across ~150 years."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"TD0211","link_text":"George Edward Cole","display_label":"Both Talcott-line cousins served as elected lawmakers","slug":"george-cole-1826"}]}